title: Allow using separate GPT2 decoder subgraphs for the initial run and the subsequent runs in BeamSearch/GreedySearch
body:
### Description
Allow using separate GPT2 decoder subgraphs for the initial run and the subsequent runs that allows for using specific optimizations in each of them as the sequence lengths are different for the initial run and the subsequent runs.

This change:
1) Adds Slice nodes at appropriate locations in the initial run subgraph to reduce unnecessary compute (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/13809#issuecomment-1338015365)

2) Modifies the input shapes of the subsequent run subgraph to reflect that the input sequence length will always be 1

3) Collects all the shared initializers between the 2 subgraphs and moves it to the main graph so that it can be shared between the 2 and thus the overhead of introducing another near-identical subgraph to the model is very low.

The kernel support to accomadate this change will come in another PR

### Motivation and Context
Same motivation as in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/13809 but an alternate design

title: QDQ quantizer not using scalar scale and zp in DequantizeLinear for per-tensor quantization

labels.name: quantization
labels.description: issues related to quantization

labels.name: ep:tvm
labels.description: issues related to TVM execution provider

body: ### Describe the issue As shown in the figure, the QDQ ONNX produced by the ONNXRuntime's quantizer has this inconsistency: the model is using per-tensor quantization, but the `DequantizeLinear` on the Conv bias is using rank-1 and size-1 tensor to represent the scale and zero point. However, the scales and zero points of weight and Conv output are scalars, which is the correct behavior for per-tensor quantization, can you fix the inconsistency on the bias quant info? This inconsistency can cause some trouble in TVM deployment flow, see https://github.com/apache/tvm/issues/13545. ### To reproduce Using `QuantFormat.QDQ` and per-tensor mode, the issue can be observed in the produced QDQ ONNX. ```python3 quantize_static( model_input=path_input, model_output=path_output, calibration_data_reader=reader_calib, nodes_to_exclude=nodes_excluded, quant_format=QuantFormat.QDQ, per_channel=False, weight_type=QuantType.QUInt8, activation_type=QuantType.QUInt8, calibrate_method=CalibrationMethod.MinMax, ) ``` ### Urgency _No response_ ### Platform Other / Unknown ### OS Version Universal ### ONNX Runtime Installation Released Package ### ONNX Runtime Version or Commit ID v1.13.1 ### ONNX Runtime API Python ### Architecture X64 ### Execution Provider Default CPU ### Execution Provider Library Version _No response_

body:
### Description
Use onnxruntime_fetchcontent_makeavailable cmake function for TRT. See the comment for the reason.


### Motivation and Context
To support a newer TRT version. Previously they have a "BUILD_EXE" build option to allow us to exclude such things from build. But in https://github.com/onnx/onnx-tensorrt/pull/879 they deleted the build option. It wouldn't be a problem if we continue to use git submodules as before, because cmake's add_subdirectories function has an "EXCLUDE_FROM_ALL" keyword.  However, cmake's FetchContent module doesn't. That's why I needed to create our own version of the macro.

title: `torch.Tensor.as_strided` yields not the same results after conversion to ONNX with `CPUExecutionProvider`
body:
### Describe the issue

Exporting a very simple PyTorch model with a `tensor.as_strided()` operation, no warning or error is raised during the export.

However, the results are different compared to PyTorch when running with ONNX Runtime. It could be related to a limited dynamic shape support.

### To reproduce

Define the model:

```python
import torch
import torch.nn as nn

class MyModel3(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()

    def forward(self, x: torch.Tensor):
        a, b, c = x.size()

        strides_original = x.stride()

        shape = (a, b // 2, 4)
        stride = (strides_original[0] // 2, strides_original[1] - 3, 3)
        
        # stride = (x[0][0][0], 4, 3)  <-- if used instead, this will raise an error

        x_strided = x.as_strided(size=shape, stride=stride)

        return x_strided
```

Export to ONNX:
```python
model = MyModel3()
x = torch.randint(8, (50, 30, 15)) + 1
res = model(x)
print(res)

torch.onnx.export(
    model,
    (x,),
    "/home/fxmarty/asstrided_model.onnx",
    input_names=["x"],
    output_names=["x_out"],
    dynamic_axes={"x":  {0: "axis0", 1: "axis1", 2: "axis2"}},
    opset_version=14
)
```

**No warning or error whatsoever is shown during the export**.

Then, compare the inference between PyTorch and ONNX Runtime with CPUExecutionProvider:

```python
import onnxruntime as ort
import numpy as np

session = ort.InferenceSession("/home/fxmarty/asstrided_model.onnx", providers=["CPUExecutionProvider"])

inp = {
    "x": np.random.randint(8, size=(45, 56, 29)) + 1,
}

res = session.run(None, inp)

model = MyModel3()
with torch.no_grad():
    res_pt = model(torch.tensor(inp["x"]))

res_ort = res[0]
res_pt_np = res_pt.numpy()

assert res_ort.shape == res_pt_np.shape

diff = np.max(np.abs(res_ort - res_pt_np))
print(f"[x] Maxdiff: {diff}")
```

Prints:
```
[x] Maxdiff: 0.9846013188362122
```

Same issue doing the export with opset 15, 16, 17.

---
PyTorch version: 1.13.1

@justinchuby https://www.justinchuby.com/torch-onnx-op-matrix/ shows `Broken support` for `as_strided`, is it related to my issue? In https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/80039 `as_strided` is marked as supported so not sure.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/9808326/206796334-f05da409-8b19-4359-822f-62f0c54875a0.png)

Thanks everyone!

title: [Feature Request] Define a Python exception hierarchy

labels.name: feature request
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

body:
### Describe the feature request

All C++ exceptions are translated to Python exceptions whose base class is [`Exception`](https://docs.python.org/3/library/exceptions.html#Exception). This is inconvenient because catching `onnxruntime` specific exceptions is not easy or very cumbersone and error prone.

An `onnxruntime` specific base class, say `onnxruntime.Error` should be defined to explicitly contruct an `onnxruntime` exception hierarcy.

### Describe scenario use case

Currently to catch exceptions raised by onnxruntime one has to write
```
try:
    ...
except Exception as exc:
    ...
```
ad inspect `exc` and re-raise it if it not a `onnxruntime` exception.

A second approach is to be more explicit and verbose:
```
from onnxruntime.capi.onnxruntime_pybind11_state import (
    EPFail,
    EngineError,
    Fail,
    InvalidArgument,
    InvalidGraph,
    InvalidProtobuf,
    ModelLoaded,
    NoModel,
    NoSuchFile,
    NotImplemented,
    RuntimeException,
)

try:
    ...
except (
    EPFail,
    EngineError,
    Fail,
    InvalidArgument,
    InvalidGraph,
    InvalidProtobuf,
    ModelLoaded,
    NoModel,
    NoSuchFile,
    NotImplemented,
    RuntimeException,
) as exc:
    ...
```

If an explicit onnxruntime exception hierarcy is defined, this could simply be
```
import onnxruntime

try:
    ...
except onnxruntime.Error as exc:
    ...
```

A quick check to the `pybind11` [Exceptions docs](https://pybind11.readthedocs.io/en/stable/advanced/exceptions.html?highlight=exceptions#exceptions) shows that it should be quite straightforward to implement this feature.

title: Support for custom op variadic inputs/outputs
body:
### Description
Adds support for variadic inputs and outputs to custom operators.

Custom op tests:
- [x] 1 variadic input (string) and 1 variadic output (int64_t)
  - Called with 3 input strings => generates 3 output int64_ts
- [x] 2 inputs (1 required, 1 variadic) and 2 outputs (1 required, 1 variadic)
  - Called with 3 input strings (last 2 are variadic) => generates 3 output int64_ts (last 2 are variadic)
- [x] Error expected: variadic input is not last
- [x] Error expected: variadic output is not last
- [x] 1 variadic input (undefined type) and 1 variadic output (undefined type); heterogeneous element types.
  - Called with inputs (string, int64_t, float) => echos outputs in reversed order (float, int64_t, string)
- [x] Error expected: variadic input minimum arity violation
- [x] Error expected: variadic output minimum arity violation
- [x] Error expected: pass differing input element types when `GetVariadicInputHomogeneity()` returns `true`
- [ ] Error expected: pass differing output element types when `GetVariadicOutputHomogeneity()` returns `true`

### Motivation and Context
Needed for [custom ops that wrap external runtimes/models](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/13427) and maybe [TensorRT plugins](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/13847).

title: Use cache for compilation in container
body:
### Description
For compilation in container,  ADO Cache task doesn't work directly.
The workaround is to mount the cache directory to the container, and let CCache in container to read/write cache data.
In short, we just leverage ADO API to download/upload cache data.

The Post-jobs works in stack-mode, So the PostBuildCleanUp Tasks should be defined first.
Thus, The PostBuildCleanUp would be executed lastly.
Else, Cache Task would fail to upload cache because the Agent Directory is cleaned.

title: CUDA provider gives different result with respect to CPU

labels.name: ep:CUDA
labels.description: issues related to the CUDA execution provider

body:
### Describe the issue



TF function [`tf.ragged.stack_dynamic_partitions`](https://www.tensorflow.org/api_docs/python/tf/ragged/stack_dynamic_partitions) when converted to onnx with tf2onnx, gives different results for CUDA and CPU providers. CUDA behavior does not follow the expected behavior (same ordering as in data).

### To reproduce

After converting the following concrete function with tf2onnx:

```python
@tf.function(
    input_signature=[
        tf.TensorSpec(shape=[None], dtype=tf.int32, name="index_batch"),
        tf.TensorSpec(shape=[None], dtype=tf.int32, name="data"),
    ]
)
def test_f(index_batch, data):
    batched_data = tf.ragged.stack_dynamic_partitions(data, index_batch, num_partitions=tf.reduce_max(index_batch) + 1)
    return batched_data

concrete = test_f.get_concrete_function()
```

The resulting onnx model sometimes gives different results when using CUDA provider:

```python
N = 257

test_f_cpu = rt.InferenceSession('test/test_f.onnx', providers=['CPUExecutionProvider'])
test_f_gpu = rt.InferenceSession('test/test_f.onnx', providers=['CUDAExecutionProvider'])

index_batch = np.random.randint(0, 10, N, "int32")
data = np.random.randint(0, 50, len(index_batch_cpu), "int32")

result_cpu = test_f_cpu .run(['output_0', 'Identity_1:0'], {'index_batch': index_batch, 'data': data})
result_gpu = test_f_gpu .run(['output_0', 'Identity_1:0'], {'index_batch': index_batch, 'data': data})

ragged_result_cpu = tf.RaggedTensor.from_row_splits(result_cpu[0], result_cpu[1])
ragged_result_gpu = tf.RaggedTensor.from_row_splits(result_gpu[0], result_gpu[1])
print([np.all(x) for x in (ragged_result_cpu==ragged_result_gpu).to_list()])
```
`[True, True, True, True, False, True, True, False, True, True, True, True, True, True, True]` 

Changing the input causes different wrong indexes. In this case, printing the elements at index 4:
```python
print(ragged_result_cpu[4].numpy())
print(ragged_result_gpu[4].numpy())
```
```
[33 29 28 41 13 20 27 30 26  1 24  9 49  9 16  2 16 29 16 33 30 22]
[22 33 29 28 41 13 20 27 30 26  1 24  9 49  9 16  2 16 29 16 33 30]
```
shows that the order of the elements is not the same. The CPU one is following the ordering of the original data array, that is the expected behavior. In my case the issue starts with N>256, regardless of the number of batches.

Colab reproduction: https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1QfWOiositnSCLMxqqNWJ_UyKz1_WebvX?usp=sharing
onnx model: [test_f.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/10219589/test_f.zip)

Ubuntu 20.04

onnxruntime-gpu 1.13.1

title: [ORTModule] TorchScript Fallback

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
The PR is to extract sub-graphs containing only light-weight Ops (such as elementwise Ops and no-Ops) and fallback the execution to PyTorch using TorchScript running for ORTModule on CUDA EP. PyTorch's TorchScript backend on CUDA EP will have nvFuser enabled by default, so that the fallback sub-graphs will have nvFuser enabled.

With this change, we observed around 3~8% perf gain on some models such as Bloom, XLNet, CLRv3, etc.
